node.text: The founder and CEO of @flybyjing Jing Gao shares how she turned her chili crisp startup into not only a viral sensation, but a vehicle to reconnect with her own identity. After raising private equity funding from @preludegrowth, Fly By Jing will soon launch in Target, Whole Foods, Sprouts, Foxtrot, Thrive Market, and Costco. Thank you for joining @csorvino & Forbes live, @jingtheory !

node.title: Viral Chili Crisp & Building A Lasting Food Brand

node.text: The biggest portion of Trump’s revenue flowed through his clubs and golf properties, which generated approximately $940 million over four years. Trump National Doral, the golf resort in Miami, contributed roughly $270 million to that total. Mar-a-Lago, Trump’s club in Palm Beach, brought in about $90 million. A New Jersey golf club, where the former president has been spending time this summer, took in $60 million or so. Those top-line figures didn’t all end up in Trump’s pocket, however. Golf clubs and resorts are expensive to manage, with operating profit margins running at 20% in good times. During the pandemic, Trump’s traditional courses fared reasonably well, but his golf resorts had to contend with long shutdowns, causing his overall golf and club revenues to drop 27% to an estimated $190 million in 2020.

node.title: Trump’s Business Hauled In $2.4 Billion During His Four Years As President

node.text: This episode of Building Fortunes takes a look at Sheila Johnson's career rise. Johnson cofounded cable TV channel Black Entertainment Network in 1979 with her then-husband Robert. Viacom bought it for $2.9 billion in 2001. After her divorce in 2002, she sold off her shares and has since invested in hotels in Florida and Virginia, planes, real estate and horses. Her Innisbrook resort in Palm Harbor, Florida, hosts an annual PGA Tour championship. She was an executive producer of the critically-acclaimed 2013 film 'The Butler,' which tells the story of a former slave turned White House employee.

node.title: BET Cofounder Sheila Johnson's Path To A Multimillion Dollar Fortune

node.text: In this episode of Building Fortunes, we look at how Elton John became one of the best-selling artists of all time. In 2020, Elton John's yearly earnings amounted to $81 million. His Farewell Yellow Brick Road Tour grossed $212 million in 2019, the second-highest tally in the business. With the pandemic postponing his North American tour dates in April, the Rocket Man will have to wait to complete his 300-show, five-continent tour.

node.text: Kendra Scott is the founder of the jewelry and lifestyle brand of the same name. She first started making jewelry out of her spare bedroom in Austin, Texas in 2002 after she couldn't find color gemstone jewelry she could afford. Her creations grew into a phenomenon, with sales north of $300 million a year and giving Scott a personal fortune worth close to a half a billion dollars. But this success was not preordained. This is the story of how Kendra Scott became one of America’s richest self-made women, and the one person who kept her dream from turning into a nightmare.

node.title: Kendra Scott's Rocky Road To Gemstone Success

node.text: The world’s highest-paid athlete is clearly enjoying his vast wealth. Last week, UFC star Conor McGregor, who earned $180 million last year, unveiled a new extravagant purchase—a $3.6 million Tecnomar for Lamborghini 63 speed boat. “My Lamborghini yacht is ready,” the 33-year-old McGregor announced in an Instagram post while recovering from the leg injury he suffered in his third fight with Dustin Poirier at UFC 264 on July 10. Known as the “Supercar of the Sea,” the Lamborghini 63 is (as its name implies) 63-feet long, and powered by twin MAN V12 engines, each capable of producing 2000hp. With that kind of power, the 24-ton vessel can reach a speed of 60 knots, making it one of the fastest boats in its class. In addition to the boat’s performance, the exterior embodies the Lamborghini DNA. The verde gea green hull is the same color as the Lamborghini Sian, and the carbon-fiber superstructure (to keep the weight down) features angular windows that evoke Lambo’s famous hexagons. The cockpit is also a nautical interpretation of two Lamborghini models, with leather pilot seats from the Huracán Evo and a helm modeled on the Aventador steering wheel. node.text: Nearly ten years to the day after British R&B icon Amy Winehouse died at age 27, her work is back on the Billboard charts, thanks to a vinyl-driven surge of some of her greatest hits. The album 'Remixes' was released in the U.S. by Republic Records on July 17, featuring Winehouse hits like "Rehab" and "Love Is A Losing Game" set to electronic dance beats. 'Remixes' is a limited edition album available only in vinyl, but its sales over the past week have been enough for the work to break into the top album charts—especially in the electronic dance category. The album debuted at No. 2 on Billboard’s “Top Dance/Electronic Albums” chart, while coming in at No. 5 on the vinyl albums chart and No. 151 on the Billboard 200, which takes U.S. sales and streams of all albums into account. Republic Records is an arm of Universal Music Group, which owns the rights to Winehouse’s music, though the two albums she released while alive were under the Island Records label—which is another Universal brand. node.text: The only way to truly protect your cryptocurrency investment from hackers, exchange outages and other potential calamities is with a so-called crypto cold wallet. Using a hardware wallet means that no one can access your Bitcoin, Ethereum and other cryptocurrencies without access to the specific hardware device or its backup seed phrase. With pin codes, passwords and biometrics, hardware wallets are the best way to protect your cryptocurrency tokens while ensuring that those keys are yours and yours alone. Whether you're looking for a USB hardware wallet to take with you wherever you go or you want a metal-stamped seed phrase reminder that will survive even if your house burns down, tap the link in bio for the best cold wallets you can use to protect your Bitcoin, Ethereum and other cryptocurrencies, and head over to @forbesvetted for more shopping finds. node.text: The biggest portion of Trump’s revenue flowed through his clubs and golf properties, which generated approximately $940 million over four years. Trump National Doral, the golf resort in Miami, contributed roughly $270 million to that total. Mar-a-Lago, Trump’s club in Palm Beach, brought in about $90 million. A New Jersey golf club, where the former president has been spending time this summer, took in $60 million or so. Those top-line figures didn’t all end up in Trump’s pocket, however. Golf clubs and resorts are expensive to manage, with operating profit margins running at 20% in good times. During the pandemic, Trump’s traditional courses fared reasonably well, but his golf resorts had to contend with long shutdowns, causing his overall golf and club revenues to drop 27% to an estimated $190 million in 2020.

node.text: Jeff Bezos penned an open letter to the National Aeronautics and Space Administration this week to propose an atypical business arrangement: His space flight company, Blue Origin, will waive up to $2 billion in fees if NASA allows it to participate in its mission to return humans to the Moon. The former Amazon CEO’s letter is the latest chess move in his battle with fellow space tycoon Elon Musk. In April, NASA awarded a $2.9 billion lunar-landing contract to Musk’s SpaceX. That deal is part of the agency’s Artemis program, which aims to work with private space companies to put people back on the Moon by 2024 and establish a “long-term presence” there by 2028. In his letter, Bezos accused NASA’s selection committee of “veer[ing] from the Agency’s oft-stated procurement strategy” of working with multiple vendors by opting instead to “confer a multi-year, multi-billion-dollar head start” to SpaceX. Bezos said the “decision broke the mold of NASA’s successful commercial space programs by putting an end to meaningful competition for years to come.” Tap the link in bio for more. (📸: Blue Origin)

node.text: The Vatican owns more than 5,000 church and investment properties around the world, a central office at the Catholic Church revealed for the first time Saturday, according to several news outlets—but the church is struggling with a budget deficit, plus years of alleged mismanagement tied to its investment strategy. Most of the Vatican’s real estate holdings (4,051) are in Italy, the majority of which are used by church-affiliated groups or rented out at reduced prices instead of getting leased at market rate, according to a report from the church-run Administration of the Patrimony of the Holy See (APSA) obtained by Reuters, Catholic News Service and other outlets. APSA also reportedly holds over 1,000 properties in London, Geneva, Paris and other cities outside Italy, including a London real estate investment the Vatican controversially sank more than $400 million into nearly a decade ago. Tap the link in bio for more. (📸: AFP via Getty Images)

node.text: Depending on whom you ask, Charles Koch is a titan of industry, dark money political bogeyman or the Marcus Aurelius of the libertarian movement. But soon Koch might be known as the billionaire who persuaded Republican and Democratic holdouts to legalize cannabis at the federal level. And it’s not because he’s a pothead. Although Koch isn’t big on consuming it himself, he’s going public now with a long-held belief: Cannabis should be legal nationwide. So he’s putting his name, and nearly $25 million of his $45 billion fortune towards criminal justice reform and legalization efforts. “It should be the individual’s choice,” says Koch from his office in Koch Industries’ sprawling granite compound in Wichita, Kansas. “[Prohibition] is counterproductive. It ruins people’s lives, creates conflict in society and is anti-progress. The whole thing never made sense to me.” Koch is not alone in his view. Nearly 70% of Americans now believe cannabis should be federally legal. Currently, 18 states allow for adult-use and 37 have legalized medical marijuana, creating an industry that generated more than $17.5 billion in legal sales last year—a figure expected to balloon to $100 billion by 2030. Tap the link in bio for the full read. (📸: DAFD)
